column8: Guojie paper: we compare RNA editomes across eusocial castes, identifying ca. 11,000 RNA editing sites in gynes, large workers and small workers. column8: Gene expression of tandem-running in Temnothorax: we elucidate the transcriptomic basis of scouting, tandem-leading, and tandem-following behavior across two species with opposing lifestyles: the slavemaking Temnothorax americanus and its primary, non-parasitic host T. longispinosus.
RNA seq data from a brain transcriptome project on the ant Temnothorax longispinosus: Samples from workers from different populations engaging in attack/ no attack against the slavemaker intruder.

Following queen removal, young brood tending workers of the facultative polygynous ant Temnothorax longispinosus start to develop ovaries and engage in dominance interactions. We set out to identify caste specific genes and gene expression patterns along a reproductive gradient with the queen resembling the main reproductive phenotype, followed by reproductive nest-workers, none-reproductive nest-workers and foragers as the non-reproductive extreme. For each caste 5-10 individuals were pooled for the RNA-seq experiment.
Raw RNAseq libraries of pools of larvae, pupae, workers males and queens for the annotation of the Temnothorax longispinosus genome.

column8: We experimentally disentangled behavior (brood care vs. foraging), age (young vs. old), and fertility (fertile vs. infertile) in ant workers and investigated transcriptomic patterns linked to each factor independently
RNA from host of a slave maker ant before and during raids

The cestode Anomotaenia brevis affects the behaviour, life history and morphology of parasitized Temnothorax nylanderi ants and indirectly of their unparasitized nestmates. To gain insights on how parasites alter host phenotypes, we contrast brain gene expression patterns of T. nylanderi workers parasitized with the cestode, their unparasitized nestmates and unparasitized workers from unparasitized colonies

RNA-Seq analysis of brain transcriptomes of Temnothorax rugatulus queens and workers originating from colonies with differing social form and queen morphs: We try to study the effect of queen morph on other factors like changes in social form, reproductive caste differentiation and worker caste differentiation in the ant Temnothorax rugatulus. This is the first study to our knowledge to disentangle the two factors queen morph and social form and to investigate the effects of each factor as well as the interaction of both on brain gene expression in ant queens. Additionally, we show how queen morph affects gene expression depending on caste

Comparative transcriptomic analysis of the mechanisms underpinning ageing and fecundity in social insects: The exceptional longevity of queens in social insects, and how they manage to sustain lifelong high fecundity, remains a poorly understood topic in the biology of ageing. We examined gene expression between young and old queens and workers across different lineages of social insect (termites, bees, and ants). These data are derived from workers of the ant Temnothorax rugatulus (brain and fat body tissue)

column8: the clonal ant Platythyrea punctata as representative of a species with low social complexity. Colonies are small, and workers can clonally produce identical female offspring from unfertilized eggs by thelytokous parthenogenesis [39]. Despite the absence of morphological or genetic differences among totipotent nest-mates, colonies are characterized by a reproductive division of labour between one (occasionally several) reproductively dominant workers (hereafter, dominants) and a majority of subordinate, non-reproducing workers (hereafter, subordinates)
